# =============================================================================
# zynta_db_smoke.novis — integration smoke test for the NOVIS-0011 builtins
# (zynta_db_exec / zynta_db_query). Verifies that the novis -> zynta DB
# bridge actually works end-to-end against a real SQLite database.
#
# The test is run from tests/run_tests.sh with ZYNTA_DB_URL pointing at a
# unique tempfile, so successive runs don't see stale rows. The test prints
# four lines to stdout; the harness compares them byte-for-byte against
# the expected literal.
#
# Important runtime notes (so future readers know why the output looks
# the way it does):
#   * zynta_db_exec returns the affected row count (sqlite3_changes).
#   * zynta_db_query returns a zynta::Value of kind=Array, which the
#     novis runtime currently down-converts to a 1-D Tensor of doubles
#     (one element per row, value 0.0 for any non-numeric cell). This
#     means we can't read column data from inside novis yet, but the
#     *cardinality* (number of elements) of the returned Tensor is
#     faithful to the SQL result, which is what this test asserts.
#   * We use print() + a literal expected string instead of an
#     assert() because the runtime has no assert builtin yet.
# =============================================================================

# Schema bootstrap: CREATE TABLE is idempotent in SQLite, so this also
# makes the test re-runnable against a fresh temp DB without an explicit
# drop. Row count is 0 because no rows changed.
schema_changes: int = zynta_db_exec("CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS users(id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT, age INTEGER)")
print(schema_changes)

# Insert two rows. Each INSERT reports 1 affected row.
insert_alice: int = zynta_db_exec("INSERT INTO users(name, age) VALUES('alice', 30)")
print(insert_alice)

insert_bob: int = zynta_db_exec("INSERT INTO users(name, age) VALUES('bob', 25)")
print(insert_bob)

# Query — should return 2 rows. From novis we can only observe cardinality,
# but cardinality is the canonical invariant a DB integration test should
# pin down. If the bridge ever silently drops rows or panics, this test
# catches it. Each non-numeric cell becomes 0.0 in the current conversion.
rows: list = zynta_db_query("SELECT id, name, age FROM users ORDER BY id")
print(rows)
